TY  - JOUR
T1  - Note—The Single Facility Minimax Distance Problem Under Stochastic Location of Demand
AU  - Carbone, Robert
AU  - Mehrez, Abraham
Y1  - 1980/01/01
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.26.1.113
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.26.1.113
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 113
EP  - 115
VL  - 26
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This note extends the minimum maximum distance single facility location problem to situations where the locations of prospective demand points are considered to be random variables. Two types of decision are analyzed for this setting under the assumption of independent and identical normal distributions with the same means: locating on the basis of an expected value criterion or adopting a wait-and-see policy. Through the concept of the expected value of perfect information (EVPI), it is shown for one-dimensional location decisions that a substantial reduction in maximum distance may be realized by the adoption of a wait-and-see policy.
AB  - This note extends the minimum maximum distance single facility location problem to situations where the locations of prospective demand points are considered to be random variables. Two types of decision are analyzed for this setting under the assumption of independent and identical normal distributions with the same means: locating on the basis of an expected value criterion or adopting a wait-and-see policy. Through the concept of the expected value of perfect information (EVPI), it is shown for one-dimensional location decisions that a substantial reduction in maximum distance may be realized by the adoption of a wait-and-see policy.
